AGI - The reform of the EU's Single Market starts uphill to meet the challenge with China and the United States. The comparison between the Twenty-seven on Enrico Letta's report lasted almost eight hours with a pull and spring on the terms to use in the conclusions of the EU summit. The Single Market has almost forty years and has contributed to the emergence of European giants in the chemical, aeronautical and automotive sectors. But it suffers from blind points > finance, but also telecommunications, energy and defence remain sectors fragmented by different national regulations that penalize competitiveness.
&nbsp;
"There has been a very long debate because the starting positions are divergent," said French President Emmanuel Macron>, referring to the integration of capital markets at the end of the day of discussions. "This new cathedral, the Union of Savings and Investments," is the key to mobilizing private funding for our priorities. Today we have established a method, principles, a calendar, from June we will return to the topic," he added. "More than 300 billion euros leave Europe every year to invest in the United States because the European market is fragmented and not quite attractive", insisted Letta in his two days in Brussels.
&nbsp;
"The proposal for the common debt is supported by the Italian Government", said the President of the Council, Giorgia Meloni>. "Enrico Letta puts the question that was also taken up in the next debate and in the Council conclusions about the ability to reopen a debate to mobilize private capital on these challenges, to make sure that those capitals can remain in the European market instead of finding, too often, better conditions in other realities," he said. "European enterprises must be able to benefit from the economies of scale offered by such a large European internal market if we want to progress in terms of growth, competitiveness and successfully complete the major green and digital transformation projects", is the position of the German Chancellor, Olaf Scholz>.
&nbsp;
Europe is facing a wall of investment and the Union of Capital Markets must help to overcome it by mobilizing private savings for the real economy. Almost a third of the 35 thousand billion euros of European savings "love" in bank accounts, compared to less than 15% in the United States.<br> The aim of the summit was to give a new political impetus to the project, which has been involved in technical debates for 10 years, in a context of divergent national interests. The small countries, however, refuse to impose European financial supervision, particularly from France, which houses the European Authority of Financial Instruments and Markets (Esma) in Paris. The harmonization of tax law or bankruptcy is also an insurmountable enigma. "We must avoid excessive bureaucracy, excessive regulation and excessive centralization, as some states recommend," said the Luxembourg Prime Minister Luc Frieden.

